() Project Report: Smart Diet Planner

Introduction

This project focuses on solving a common problem faced by many students and young adults—confusion about diet and fitness goals. With so much information available online, people often feel overwhelmed and unsure whether they should focus on losing fat, gaining muscle, or maintaining their current physique. This lack of clarity leads to inconsistent habits and poor results.

---

Problem Statement

Many individuals, especially college students, struggle with:
Not knowing whether to cut, bulk, or maintain
Following random diet advice from social media
Lack of structured and realistic diet plans
Inconsistency due to confusion
This project addresses the need for a simple tool that can guide users in the right direction without overwhelming them.

---

Why This Problem Matters
Health and fitness play an important role in overall well-being, but students often neglect it due to academic pressure and lack of awareness. Poor diet choices can lead to low energy levels, reduced focus, and long-term health issues.

---

Approach and Solution
The solution was to create a web application that:
Takes user inputs: weight, height, and body fat percentage
Uses simple logic to determine the appropriate fitness approach
Suggests whether the user should:
Cut (fat loss)
Bulk (muscle gain)
Recomposition (balance both)
The system also calculates an estimated daily calorie intake and provides a simple diet plan based on commonly available foods.

---

Key Decisions
While building this project, several important decisions were made:
Using body fat percentage instead of only BMI:
This provides a more accurate assessment of fitness level.
Keeping the interface simple:
Avoided unnecessary complexity so that anyone can use it easily.
Providing realistic diet suggestions:
Included common foods instead of expensive or complicated meal plans.
Using basic technologies (HTML, CSS, JavaScript):
Ensured the project remains lightweight and accessible.

===

Challenges Faced
Some of the challenges encountered during this project included:
Deciding the correct logic for cut, bulk, and recomposition
Making the application simple but still meaningful
Avoiding overly technical or unrealistic diet plans
Ensuring the output feels natural and understandable

---

What I Learned
Through this project, I learned that:
Real-world problems do not always require complex solutions
Simplicity and clarity are often more effective than advanced features
Understanding user needs is more important than adding extra functionality
Basic programming can be used to create practical tools
